								<p class="lead"><strong>Now that you understand that the Web is a part of the Internet and that you access the Web through the Internet, let's learn a little bit about the text (the printed words) you see and read when you are looking at information on the Web.</strong></p class="lead">
								<hr>
								</p><H4>Hypertext Markup Language (HTML)</h4></p>
								<p>Whatever you see and read on the Web was put there by a computer user. For example, the color of the text, the <strong>font</strong> (how the letters look - also called type or typesetting), the space between words and sentences, where a picture is placed, and everything that you see was chosen by someone before it was put on the Web.</p>
								<p>So, in order for the viewer to see things on the Web the way the user intends, the user must also input instructions for how the text and other items are to be displayed. These instructions are called <strong>Hypertext Markup Language</strong> (<strong>HTML</strong> for short). HTML is the standard protocol for formatting and displaying documents on the Web. It is the formatting language or code used for Web documents and it tells Web browsers how to display the information on your computer screen.</p>
								<p>So how does HTML work? Think of it this way, while people use words to speak a language, the language of HTML is made up of tags. <strong>Tags</strong> are used on different parts of the document to tell the browser how to display it. For example, the information in a tag will instruct the browser to display the title of a document in big, bright purple text that blinks.</p>
								<p>Basically, HTML contains tags that surround text and the tags describe how the text should be displayed on the screen. Because browsers must be able to adjust to different computers, screens and windows and HTML must be able to adjust to different browsers, HTML must be flexible.</p>
								<p>HTML will display fonts that are already loaded on a user's computer and substitute fonts if the original font is not available. Therefore, the information on a Web page can look different, depending on the size of the window you are using to view it, the fonts that are located on your computer and the browser you are using. For example, if your computer does not have the font for Chinese letters, your computer will display the text using a default font that is on your computer.</p>
								<p>What if you want to print a document from the Web? Because of HTML, documents may not always keep the same formatting that you see on the Web when you print the document. However, there is a way for you to keep the format of documents that you see on the Web when you print or email them. Let's learn more about how you can do this.</p>
