							<h4>PDF, XPS and FTP</h4>
							<p>As you already learned, H T M L is the standard protocol for formatting and displaying documents on the Web. But because it is so flexible, when you try to print or email a document from the Web, the format may not stay the same as you see it on the Web. If you want to keep the format that you see, you can convert (which means change) the format of the document from HTML to another format. The two formats that do this easily are called <strong>PDF</strong> format and <strong>XPS</strong> format.</p>	
							<p><strong>Portable Document Format (PDF)</strong> is a print format that will preserve or "fix"ù all of the fonts, formatting, colors, and graphics of any document as they are set in the original and are supposed to print. It does not matter what format or program was used to originally create the document; when you convert the document to PDF, it will be saved in its original format.</p>	
							<p>Once a PDF file is created, a user must view or print the PDF document using AdobeÆ AcrobatÆ Reader&#x2122;. There is a basic version of AdobeÆ Reader&#x2122; which is free and easy to <strong>download</strong> (which means to copy data from the Web or Internet to your computer) to your computer.</p>
							<p>If you want to create or change a PDF file, you must purchase AdobeÆ AcrobatÆ, or other software that creates PDF files, or download an add-in that allows you to save a printout in PDF format. PDF files are commonly found and shared on the Internet. Many newer versions of Microsoft Word or other word processing software have the option to save a document as a PDF built in. Remember, once a document is converted to PDF, it is not easy to make changes to the text or to the format.</p>
														<p>In the section on Word Processing, you will learn how to create a PDF and XPS. If you do not already have the ability to create PDF on your computer, you will need to download the CutePDF writer or some other program like it at that time.</p>
							<p><strong>XML Paper Specification (XPS)</strong> is another print, fixed-layout format that preserves document formatting and cannot be easily changed. You can select this format when saving a document and the document can be viewed and printed by a browser. The format is available in Microsoft Office 2007 and add-ins can be downloaded to save in this format for other versions. Once a document is converted to XPS, it is not easy to make changes to the text or to the format.</p>
							<p>Any document that is ready to print can be converted to PDF or XPS formats. There are two benefits to converting documents to a PDF or XPS format. It allows the user keep the original document format when viewing, printing or sending by email and the viewer cannot easily change the document.</p>
							<p><strong>Uploading</strong> (which means to transfer data or files from your computer to another computer through the Internet) typically requires special software unless the site you are on, like this one, has already set up the process that allows you to upload files. The software that transfers files from one computer to another through the Internet is called <strong>File Transfer Protocol (FTP) software</strong>.</p>
 

<p>Many browsers have add-on applications that accomplish uploading. Because you must have permission to upload files to another computer, you probably will not be uploading files to other computers unless you are given permission and asked to do so. Email can be used to send files to other people through email attachments. You will be learning about email attachments later in this section.</p>

